>meer jonge energierijke mensen in leiderschapsposities en enge oude witte mannetjes ontslaan
Ze hebben onze generatie gestolen van woorden als leiderschap, vrijheid en liefde. We mogen niet meer aan een ideaal hechten zonder een vleugje ironie want anders ben je een gek. Proberen jullie ook om altijd te raden warom mensen dingen doen? Zelf bewustzijn is het toppunt van evolutie. Hoe kan het dat mensen zo anders geworden zijn? Het is zo willekeurig, de menselijke ervaring. Zo spontaan. Ik zet mij vaak ook in iemand anders bewustzijn en kijk ik naar mijn eigen en vraag ik me af in welke plek ik gezet zal worden in diens brein. Hoe ervaren zei hun omgeving? Hoe zou ik het leven interpreteren als deze persoon zijnde? Wat denk deze persoon over mijn postuur? Fascinerend. Ik las een verhaal over slavernij en kannibalisme in Congo, een gast vroeg daar een mes aan een blanke gast, ging even buiten, snijdt kleine slaaf meisje haar keel open en eten ze hem op als het niets is.

Te veel internet, we zijn onze realiteit aan het verlaten. Duizenden palen hier per dag. Korte attentie. Elke paal is een nieuwe verhaal, we springen constant om een nieuwe dopamine hit te krijgen en ons weer af te staan van er echt aan toe is te zijn. We leven allemaal in een status van verlamming.

Niemand is thuis. Iedereen is op het internet. Ik ben ook hier. Is er een ontsnappen aan? Of is de realizatie zelf een ontsnapping? Of is het erger omdat ik het realizeer maar niet kan ontsnappen? Ik heb informatie. Ik heb data. Jullie ook. Apocaplypse nadert maar we doen er niets aan. Dit is niet goed, maar we zijn hier, en morgen ook. Misschien moet ik ECHT gek worden om te ontsnappen.

Dawno dawno tymu, za siedmioma chujami, za siedmioma zekami, w okolicach Gubałówki mieszkał Tomisław Apoloniusz Curuś Bachleda Farrell, jak ten piecyk z dmuchawą. Pewnego dnia Tomisław wysedł na halę i pomyśloł: Krucafuks dość! Ile mozna wpierdalać łoscypek! Ani to dobre, ani śwarne a jakie drogie jebane!No i sracka murowana, toć to gołymi łapami ługniotane. Zeby to jeszcze z krowiego mleka było; a weź tu łodróznij barana od łowiecki. Stąd ten słonawy posmak.Tfu, łohydne. Co te turysty w tym widzą. Podczas, gdy Bachleda zajadał się łoscypkiem, smród baraniego nabiału niósł się po łokolicy. Nawet pod wiater jebało napletkiem hej! Bekasy nie wytsymały. Fetor przepłoszył je z terenów lęgowych. Ryby, w Morskim Łoku zdechły, a w Carnym Stawie, zdechły. Niedźwiedź Gąsienica łobudził się ze snu zimowego i łod razu poszedł pod prysznic. Lecz to nie tylko łod niego tak popierdalało. Niby po kąpieli smród bełta i gówna ustąpił, ale przez to woń łoctówy stała się jeszcze bardziej nieznośna. Lecz specyficzny zapach łobudził nie tyko misia, łobudził też ządze, łobrzydliwe homoseksualne żądze. Śniezny Kockodan, przez niektórych nazywany też Yeti, dostaje smergla, gdy pocuje woń fiuta hej. Tak się składo, że łoscypek pachnie tożsamo, koniec.

Bestia normalnie żywi się owocami, ale łocet budzi w niej zboczenie. Tamtej nocy zeszła z wierchu na hale wiedziona zapachem rozporka. Nieświadomy nicego Bachleda Farrell zajadoł właśnie syr. Pierwsze razy posły w dupe hej! Little Boy małpy rozdupcył Hirosimę Bachledy. Potem Kockodan założył strapona "Big Ben" i dzwonił jajami o brodę Curusia. Koszmar małpy trwał kilka dni. Depends on the book. Books written for natives will require a pretty high vocabulary not to get frustrated, but you can still read those books, it's just going to require work, looking up each word and going sentence by sentence. There's also graded readers for various levels which are books meant for learners and they limit themselves to the most common words and simpler sentences. With 1000 words you can actually start reading some books meant for beginners and work your way up to native material.

I don't know what your TL is, but Olly Richards has a bunch of short story collections in various languages, usually one for beginners and one for intermediate. You can comfortably start with those kinds of books. Usually you can find these books by googling "graded readers in X language at Y level".

My current strategy is to read one book that's on my current level where I know like 95% of the words and just get into the flow of reading without straining (extensive reading), and one book that's above my level and where I have to lookup a lot of words and strain myself (intensive reading).

>>175565698
you're missing something here
Anki is only efficient when you can't read yet, i.e. when you're a beginner/intermediate

as soon as you can read, it is more efficient to just read and look up words in the dictionary, because those rare words are rare for a reason, if there's some rare word that you need to use a lot, then you will come to know it naturally and the words that you don't know you will forget anyway, even with Anki. I don't see the point of learning such vocabulary, when you can easily look it up nowadays.

Also rare words can be classified into two groups: rarely used adjectives/verbs (used in poetry and literature) OR technical vocabulary
In the first case you can just look them up as you read, in the second case though, if there's a lot of it, like medical vocabulary, then yeah, people are already using Anki for it. But if it's some more loose vocabulary, like in engineering, then the only way you can learn it is through working with whatever the words are describing really.

So Anki is only useful for lots of hard to remember, unconnected words

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>175566591
>if there's some rare word that you need to use a lot, then you will come to know it naturally

I disagree with this point. I used to think like you that I would naturally build a vocabulary through reading a lot. Whenever I would see an unfamiliar word, I'd look it up and then move on. But the rare words didn't stick becuase there would be too much time in between reading said rare words such that I wouldn't memorize them. Once I threw those words into Anki, memorizing the words was a cinch.

In my opinion, if a word is coming up so much that you simply learn it without much effort, then it isn't that rare in the first place. In at least Engish, there are rare words that are important to learn as they capture concepts that are not adequately captured by more common words. (e.g., a word like "metonymy.")

Now, I sort of agree with you in a sense that there are indeed words that are rare because they are esoteric or archaic, and it's valid to make a judgment call on whether a word is worth learning or not. But that's not the case for all rare words, and the rare words that are worth learning are most efficiently learned through Anki.

>Anki is only useful for lots of hard to remember, unconnected words
which is why it's exactly helpful for learning rare NL words...

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>175566857
>In my opinion, if a word is coming up so much that you simply learn it without much effort, then it isn't that rare in the first place
I didn't say you shouldn't put any effort

>In at least Engish, there are rare words that are important to learn as they capture concepts that are not adequately captured by more common words. (e.g., a word like "metonymy.")
Yeah exactly. In my opinion if you see a new word like that and see that it describes a useful concept that you've never heard of before, then you should ponder that word for a bit and then start incorporating it into your speech when appropriate.

But again, in the real world (as in daily life, and in speech in general) people rarely use such words, unless they're sure that the other party knows the definition. When you discuss with another person that you don't have a lot in common with, in practice you usually try to find the simplest definitions. Now I'm not saying that those "rare" words aren't useful, but they usually require some effort to understand the concept behind them, because they're usually more abstract.

So I guess Anki can make it easier to ponder those concepts more frequently, but in my opinion if you see a word like that a few times while reading, and look up the definition, sit on it for a bit and try to understand it, you will remember it, because the concept is more important than the word itself. So in my view Anki is just not worth setting up for this. But it might be worth it for you.

>>175588779
IIRC, бы is a remnant of the aorist tense of быть. "Я бы видeл" (I would see, Ich würde sehen). Compare Slovak "Ja by som videl" (Or more common "Videl by som") which, just like Russian looks "by" + past tense, and Czech "Já bych viděl" (or "Viděl bych") which shows that it actually is "бы быть" + l-participle and not "бы" + past tense. Czech has "bych, bys, by, bychom, byste, by" for 1st-3rd person sg. and pl. In Slovak amd Czech those forms got lost/devolved into "by + byť".
Slovak and Czech can also do conditionals in the past by using "by + past tense of byť + l-participle": "Ja by som bol videl / Bol by som videl" / "Já bych byl viděl / Byl bych viděl". (I would have seen, Ich hätte gesehen). Not sure if Russian can do the same.
I also remember reading about aorist still being present in some south slavic languages, so maybe it is also used for conditionals there.

posts.com:
>>175551055
>Hast du irgendeine Schwester?
Use "eine". "Irgendeine" sounds like "any kind of sister"
>Gibt das bitte an deiner Mutter.
Gib das hier bitte deiner Mutter. "an deiner Mutter (dat.)" means "At your mother". There is a construct with "an" that is close in meaning "etwas an jemanden (acc.) weitergeben" meaning "passing something (like a message) onto somebody.

>Mary hat eine Gruppe beigetretet, für Witwe über ihre Betrübnis zu reden.
Mary ist einer Gruppe für Witwen beigetreten, um über ihre Trauer zu reden/sprechen.
Learn which verbs form the Perfekt with haben and which ones with sein.
>Opa, wieso redet Du und Oma zusammen nicht mehr?
...reden du und Oma nicht mehr miteinander.
You don't talk "together", but "with each other". Capitalizing Du is only done in formal writing, like letters to show respect. It's like a medium stage between du and Sie. You probably wouldn't use it when transcribing dialogue or in casual emails.
>Auch wenn Herr Smiths Frau krank oder gemein würde, würde er sich von ihr nie scheiden lassen.
Selbst wenn Herr Smiths Frau krank oder gemein werden würde, würde er sich nie von ihr scheiden lassen.
You would use "auch" if you had listed other things that wouldn't be a cause for devorce before this sentence ("and even if"). Here you use "selbst" becaude you are listing only those things, which are an extreme case to illustrate the stability of their marriage.
You could technically use subjunctive II of "werden" instead of "werden würde" like you did, but because werden is used to circumscribe the subjunctive, using the subjubctive of "werden" sounds weird and is rarely done.
The word order in the main clause is technically correct, but sounds unnatural.

>>175551055
>Meine Stieftochter hat mir gesagt,
Fine so far
>dass ihr biologische Vater sie missgebraucht,
-> dass ihr leiblicher Vater sie missbrauche,
This is indirect speech, so you have a couple options. First is mode:
-Indikativ. Used casually, but in reality using it means that you knkw that the abuse is actually happening. Since the in this situation it is technically only heresay, using it is not correct.
- Konjunktiv I. This is correct for indirect speech, and the one I used. It does however sound overly formal, and yoy seldom hear it.
- Konjunktiv II. Wrong in this situation. Used only if Konjunktiv I = Indikativ
- würden + infinitiv. Possible as a replacement for Konjunktiv I. Probably easier to learn and you'll sound more natural. ("dass er sie missbrauchen würde," or "er würde sie missbrauchen")
As for the Tense, all of these are in the Präsens since the abuse is still going on. (that he was abusing her). If the original had been in present perfect (that he has been abusing her) you would use Perfekt (dass er sie missbraucht habe). For past perfect (that he had been abusing her) you use Plusquamperfekt (dass er sie missbraucht hätte)
>aber bevor ich ihn konfrontieren könnte,
-> konnte
>rufte ihre Mutter die Polizei und ließ ihn verhaftet werden.
-> rufen is irregular (strong) so the Präteritum is "rief ihre Mutter die Polizei". Verhaften is a normal verb so it's just "ließ ihn verhaften."

>>175596514
It helps to break it down into easier chunks. I'm learning Thai, and I found it easier to focus on the sounds of letters while ignoring tone at first. I focused more on how words were written than how they sounded, since I couldn't hear the difference yet.
Once you're confident with the sounds, you can add in tones. I practiced listening to a mix of Thai youtube videos for Thais and some for Thai learners. Listening to the exaggerated tones in the learning videos has helped me to be able to hear tones in normal speech now. There's a channel called Slow Vietnamese which looks similar to what I watched.
Really you just have to be patient and chug along slowly for the first 2 months where you really can't say or understand much. But once you get over the hump, it's not too tough. Something like Spanish or German is the opposite, where it's easy to start, but then the verb conjugations and noun cases start piling up.

>>175602920
Any of the Polynesian languages. Maori, Hawaiian, etc.

Tenses, gender (there is no gender in the Maori language), number, and other such features shown by inflection in English are given by particles in Maori; example:

i kata = laughed, kua kata = has just laughed, e kata ana = is laughing, ka kata = will laugh. This is regular for all verbs in passive. To make “kata” active a -ina is added by the particle remained the same i.e. i kataina = was laughed about/laughed at, ka kataina = will be laughed about.

i kii = said, kua kii = was just saying, e kii ana = saying, ka kii = will say, e kiia ana = is being said.

i kauhoe = swam, e kauhoe ana = is swimming, ka kauhoe = will swim, ka kauhoetia = will be swum.

Words that have different forms for gender don’t occur ( note that in English these distinctions are disappearing also) such as actor and actress, aviator and aviatrix, tiger and tigress, manager and manageress are all just one term in Maori: kaitapere, kaiwhakarere, taika, kaiwhakahaere that encompass both genders. If gender needs expressing this is done by adding wahine for woman/female or taane man/male. Personal pronouns he and she, him and her are both given by “ia” and his and her by tona/ona, toona/oona or taana/aana depending upon context.

Schreibe etwas über dich selbst: Erzähle etwas über deine Persönlichkeit, deine Interessen und deine Hobbys. Versuche, dich von der Masse abzuheben, indem du etwas Einzigartiges über dich schreibst.

Sei ehrlich: Vermeide es, dich anders darzustellen, als du wirklich bist. Sei ehrlich über deine Gedanken, Gefühle und Vorlieben.

Zeige deine Persönlichkeit: Verwende dein Profil, um deine Persönlichkeit zu zeigen. Verwende Humor und zeige, dass du eine positive Einstellung hast.

Sei spezifisch: Statt allgemeine Aussagen zu machen, sei spezifisch und gib Beispiele dafür, was du magst und was du tust.

Verwende gute Fotos: Verwende Fotos, die dich von deiner besten Seite zeigen und die aktuell sind. Vermeide es, Fotos zu verwenden, die dich mit anderen Menschen zeigen, die nicht deutlich erkennbar sind.

Sei vorsichtig mit persönlichen Informationen: Vermeide es, zu viele persönliche Informationen preiszugeben, wie deine Adresse oder deine Telefonnummer. Warte, bis du dich sicher genug fühlst, um diese Informationen mit jemandem zu teilen, den du online kennengelernt hast.

posts.com:
Detenuti evasi dal carcere Beccaria, in tre rientrano convinti da genitori e nonna: “Istituto senza direttore da anni”

Tre dei sette giovani detenuti evasi nel pomeriggio di Natale dal carcere minorile Beccaria sono rientrati nell’istituto milanese dopo la mediazione di genitori e parenti. I primi due, entrambi maggiorenni, sono stati convinti dalla nonna e dalla sorella. L’anziana donna ha telefonato ai carabinieri comunicando che il nipote si trovava nella sua abitazione. La sorella invece dell’altro giovane detenuto, grazie anche alla mediazione dell’istituto minorile, è riuscita a far ragionare il ragazzo e a farlo rientrare in serata.


Nella mattinata di Santo Stefano il terzo dei sette evasi è rientrato nel carcere Beccaria dopo l’opera di convincimento dei genitori. Restano tutt’ora ricercati i quattro giovani. Ad evadere poco dopo le 16 del 25 dicembre sono stati due 18enni, un 19enne e quattro 17enni, tutti nel carcere minorile in custodia cautelare per piccoli reati contro il patrimonio.

I sette avrebbero approfittato dei lavori in corso nel “cortile passeggi”, aprendosi un varco nella recinzione e scavalcando il muro di cinta. Alla notizia dell’evasione alcuni detenuti hanno appiccato il fuoco all’interno del cortile carcere per protesta. Sul posto sono intervenuti i vigili del fuoco, con diversi mezzi, che hanno subito domato le fiamme.

Un episodio che riaccende le polemiche sulla gestione del carcere minorile milanese, senza direttore da troppi anni e con una serie di lavori in corso che rendono la struttura un cantiere a cielo aperto. La direttrice facente funzioni è infatti Maria Vittoria Menenti, che si divide tre giorni alla settimana tra il Beccaria e il supercarcere di Opera di cui è vicedirettrice.

Extra Flags is an open-source userscript that lets you choose regional flags, like states and provinces, to add the already existing national flags on /int/, /pol/, /sp/, and /bant/.
